definition.value: The parent member of the class of aplysiatoxins. It is a cyanotoxin produced by several species of freshwater and marine cyanobacteria, as well as algae and molluscs.

A member of the class of aplysiatoxins that has the structure of the parent aplysiatoxin, but is carrying an additional bromo substituent on the benzene ring at the position ortho to the phenolic hydroxy group. It is a cyanotoxin produced by several species of freshwater and marine cyanobacteria, as well as algae and molluscs.

A benzaldehyde that is salicylaldehyde which is substituted at position 6 by a (3R,4S,5E)-3,4-dihydroxyhepta-1,5-dien-1-yl group. It is a phytotoxic metabolite, isolated from the rice blast fungi Magnaporthe oryzae and Magnaporthe grisea.
A pyrimidotriazine that is 1,6-dimethyl-1,5,6,7-tetrahydropyrimido[5,4-e][1,2,4]triazine with oxo groups at positions 5 and 7.
A flavonolignan isolated from Silybum marianum.
A cadinene sesquiterpene that consists of 1-(propan-2-yl)-1,2,4a,5,6,8a-hexahydronaphthalene having two methyl substituents at positions 1 and 4 (the 1S,4aS,8aS-configuration).
A monocarboxylic acid that is the O-phenyl derivative of glycolic acid. A metabolite of 2-phenoxyethanol, it is used in the manufacture of pharmaceuticals, pesticides, fungicides and dyes.
A 5-ethenyl-1,3-oxazolidine-2-thione that has S-configuration. It is a constituent of a traditional Chinese herbal medicine, Radix isatidis.
